  <text>
      <body>
         <p>Dear Friend–</p>
         <p>I am well pleased with your getting me the Books for my friends. I will what and see if they order more. For the first time in m life, I send you money. I must sell the Teapots and recover my sovereign. They are sent in mistake. I meant two quart ale or milk or water tankards without covers and one pint. I enclose for this a pound for <persName ref="prsn:Otle01">Mr Otley's</persName> Acct and 15/6 for <persName ref="prsn:Pear01">Mr Pearce's</persName>. I am off to <placeName ref="tgn:7010597">Liverpool</placeName> to morrow and thence to <placeName ref="tgn:7010955">Birmingham</placeName> and <placeName ref="tgn:7011781">London</placeName>. I send you a dozen of the Discussions thinking you may find some customers for them. In addition to this, I shall owe you a Diegesis and Volney's Researches. I have preached or lectured ten times within the last eight days and finish my season in criticism on Owenism tonight.</p> 
         <p>[[2]] I am not aware of any twopenny Social Bible by <persName ref="prsn:Owen01">Owen</persName>.</p>
         <p>I did touch <placeName ref="tgn:7008171">Yorkshire</placeName> at <placeName ref="tgn:1030487">Saddleworth</placeName> on friday and saturday and that must suffice for this year.</p> 
         <p>I mentioned my Missionary Friend to stop mouths here who say that all I care about is the pennies. I am improving my audiences in quality. The low Catholics came first but now they do not. A few respectable people creep in. I never despaired of working my way in spite of Radicals and the Devil. I shall beat them both.</p>
         <p>You shall not fail to hear from me when I can send you any thing interesting: but you must not expect to hear until february. I am about to bring the Mistress out again and to give her a fair trial.</p>
         <p>I have not much time to sermonize today as I am packing up and getting ready to be off.</p> 
         <p>[[3]] <persName ref="prsn:Carl02">T.P.C.</persName> has not a shop yet. I am not at all sure of his sufficient steadiness and application to it. He thinks a great deal more about the theatre and that sort of  nonsense, beyond what I approve.</p>
         <p>I may find a word or two more to say before I close this parcel ; but at present I am exhausted.— am sorry to hear <persName ref="prsn:Turt02">T.T.'s <choice><abbr>Junr</abbr><expan>Junior</expan></choice></persName> health is not good.</p>
         <p>Respectfully,</p> 
         <p><supplied>R Carlile</supplied></p>
         <p>P.S. respects to <persName ref="prsn:Turt03">Mrs Turton</persName>, <persName ref="prsn:Carl04">Jane</persName>, <persName ref="prsn:Carl05">Mary Ann</persName> and <persName ref="prsn:Cros01">Mrs Cross</persName>. I don't forget that <persName ref="prsn:Carl05">Mary Ann</persName> is a warm partisan of mine.</p> 
            
         <p>[[4]] I have sent the Invoice of the Books to <placeName ref="tgn:7011128"><choice><abbr>Gloster</abbr><expan>Gloucester</expan></choice></placeName></p>
      </body>
